{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512564"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11919"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11919"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.07,0.01,0.02,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108612"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4516"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90981"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"3514"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4352"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40004"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43280"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108612"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for an antenatal review at 28 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Her father has type 2 diabetes mellitus. On examination, she appears well with a BMI of 32 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. An oral glucose tolerance test with 75 g glucose was carried out for screening which showed:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting plasma glucose: 6.4 mmol/L (\u0026lt;5.3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1-hour plasma glucose: 8.5 mmol/L (\u0026lt;10.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2-hour plasma glucose: 7.7 mmol/L (\u0026lt;9.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gestational diabetes mellitus","Overt diabetes in pregnancy","Type 1 diabetes mellitus","Type 2 diabetes mellitus","Pregestational diabetes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Egestational diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E (GDM) based on the updated 2025 Australian guidelines. All patients should be offered routine antenatal testing for GDM using the oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) at 24-28 weeks gestation. In pregnancy, hormones including human placental lactogen, cortisol and progesterone have insulin-antagonising effects. This results in a degree of insulin resistance, which in turn leads to hyperglycaemia if the pancreas is unable to produce enough insulin to compensate. Under the new guidelines, GDM is diagnosed when one or more of the following criteria are met during a 75g OGTT: fasting plasma glucose 5.3-6.9 mmol/L, 1-hour plasma glucose \u226510.6 mmol/L, or 2-hour plasma glucose 9.0-11.0 mmol/L. This patient meets the fasting glucose criterion with a level of 6.4 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvert diabetes in pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E (Previously termed \u0022diabetes in pregnancy\u0022) is a distinct entity from GDM. The key difference is that overt DIP represents more severe hyperglycaemia that meets the diagnostic criteria for diabetes outside of pregnancy. Under the 2025 guidelines, overt DIP is diagnosed when fasting plasma glucose \u22657.0 mmol/L, 2-hour plasma glucose \u226511.1 mmol/L following OGTT, and/or HbA\u003Csub\u003E1c\u003C/sub\u003E \u22656.5%. This patient does not meet these more stringent criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregestational diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E refers to type 1 or type 2 diabetes mellitus that is pre-existing, or diagnosed before pregnancy. This patient has no pre-existing diagnosis, so this term would not apply here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E (T2DM) is a state of insulin resistance and relative insulin deficiency. While this patient has risk factors for T2DM (family history, high BMI), she does not have a pre-existing diagnosis. The diagnosis would typically be made outside of pregnancy, however if she met the criteria for T2DM, the patient would rather be diagnosed with overt diabetes in pregnancy as this is the first presentation during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition resulting in insulin deficiency that usually presents in childhood or early adulthood with more severe hyperglycaemia or diabetic ketoacidosis. It is less common than T2DM and gestational diabetes in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe 2025 Australian guidelines have updated the diagnostic thresholds for GDM, with the fasting glucose criterion now being 5.3-6.9 mmol/L (previously \u0026lt;5.1 mmol/L), reflecting international harmonisation of diagnostic criteria. It\u0027s important to note that while GDM typically resolves after pregnancy, women with GDM are at increased risk of developing T2DM later in life. Therefore, follow-up testing after pregnancy is crucial for these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse:collapse;width:100%;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003ECondition\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EFasting Glucose\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003E1-hour Glucose\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003E2-hour Glucose\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EHbA\u003Csub\u003E1c\u003C/sub\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EGestational Diabetes Mellitus\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E5.3-6.9 mmol/L\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u226510.6 mmol/L\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E9.0-11.0 mmol/L\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENot used for diagnosis\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EOvert Diabetes in Pregnancy\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u22657.0 mmol/L\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENot specified\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u226511.1 mmol/L\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u22656.5%\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gestational diabetes mellitus should be tested for between 24 and 28 weeks of gestation.","GDM occurs due to pregnancy hormones that have antagonistic effects on insulin, particularly human placental lactogen, cortisol, and progesterone.","Diabetes in pregnancy is diagnosed when the criteria for diabetes outside of pregnancy are met."],"references":["Sweeting A, Hare MJL, de\u202fJersey SJ, Shub AL, Zinga J, Foged C, Hall RM, Wong T, Simmons D. Australasian Diabetes in Pregnancy Society (ADIPS) 2025 consensus recommendations for the screening, diagnosis and classification of gestational diabetes. Med J Aust\u202f. 2025 Jun\u202f23;223(3). Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2025/223/3/australasian-diabetes-pregnancy-society-adips-2025-consensus-recommendations","Nankervis A, McIntyre HD, Moses RG, Ross GP, Callaway LK. Testing for gestational diabetes mellitus in Australia. Diabetes Care. 2013;36(5):e64. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3631863/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90981"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11919"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90981"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-12T12:58:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T13:00:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4516"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108612"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"81","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/81"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diabetes mellitus","s